TODO: Persona-based chat endpoint with topic guardrailing
Add a new direct endpoint (e.g. POST /chat/store-clerk or a generic POST /chat/:persona)
that bypasses the agent loop (direct generate() call, like the endpoints above) and:
  - Uses a crafted system prompt to simulate a specific persona (e.g. a food-store clerk).
  - Enforces topic boundaries: politely refuses off-topic questions
    ("I'm sorry, I'm just a clerk here — I can only help with food-related questions!").
  - Option A (simple): single model + single call — system prompt enforces both role and guardrail.
  - Option B (robust): two-step guard — phi4-mini (AGENT_MODEL_ROUTER_MODEL) classifies
    on-topic/off-topic first; main model (llama3.1:8b-instruct-q8_0, AGENT_MODEL_FAST)
    responds in character only when on-topic.
  - Request body: { message: string, storeContext?: string, conversationHistory?: {role, content}[] }
    storeContext can inject a product catalog, daily specials, store hours, etc.
  - Reuse existing rate-limiting and timeout infrastructure from this file.
Good fit for small businesses wanting a domain-specific chatbot at zero ongoing cost (local Ollama).

TODO: Optional cloud LLM provider layer (secondary priority — local-first remains the focus)
Add an opt-in abstraction that allows routing specific profiles to a cloud API instead of Ollama.
  - Introduce an ILlmProvider interface in packages/llm/types.ts with generate() and
    generateWithMetadata() methods, so Ollama becomes one provider among many.
  - Add an OpenAI-compatible provider (packages/llm/openai-compat-provider.ts) that works with:
    • GitHub Models (https://models.inference.ai.azure.com) — free tier with GitHub Pro
    • OpenAI (api.openai.com)
    • OpenRouter (openrouter.ai) — single key, many models
    • Anthropic (with minor adaptation)
  - Add a "cloud" ModelProfile to the model router; when CLOUD_LLM_API_KEY is unset,
    the profile silently falls back to the local default (zero disruption).
  - New env vars: CLOUD_LLM_PROVIDER, CLOUD_LLM_BASE_URL, CLOUD_LLM_API_KEY, CLOUD_LLM_MODEL.
  - Router integration: either force "cloud" per-request via profile param, or let the
    rules/model router escalate to cloud for tasks that exceed local model capability.
  - Keep it 100 % optional — no API key means the system behaves exactly as before.

DEFERRED: Context overflow pause (Phase 2C)
When context exceeds AGENT_BUDGET_MAX_CONTEXT_CHARS, pause the loop and return a structured
"context_overflow" status with a condensed summary, allowing the client to decide whether to
continue with reduced context or rephrase the task. Requires a /run API contract update
(status field, resumeContext support). Deferred to avoid breaking the current simple
request/response contract.

DONE: MCP bridge integration (Phase 4B)
Manna now supports MCP (Model Context Protocol) server loading at startup via `packages/mcp/`.
Configured servers are discovered from `data/mcp-servers.json`, their tools are wrapped as native
`ITool` entries (`mcp_<server>__<tool>`), and unreachable servers are skipped fail-open.

TODO (PR5): Auth gateway wrapper
Add a thin authentication gateway service that sits in front of Manna and handles all auth
concerns without touching the core agent server.
  - Create apps/gateway/ (or a single-file gateway service) that:
    • Validates API keys from the Authorization: Bearer <key> header against env vars.
    • Proxies all authenticated requests to MANNA_URL (default http://manna:3001).
    • Adds rate-limiting, CORS, and request logging at the gateway level.
  - Register as a separate docker-compose service (gateway service on port 8080).
  - New env vars: GATEWAY_API_KEYS (comma-separated), MANNA_URL, GATEWAY_PORT.
  - Manna itself stays completely untouched (no auth logic in the agent server).
  - Pattern: Client → [Gateway :8080] → [Manna :3001]
  - Reference: Express http-proxy-middleware + express-rate-limit.
  - Priority: LOW — local-only Manna does not need auth. Implement when deploying publicly.
  - Reference discussion: see prior conversation context (auth middleware Q&A).




TODO: Self-upgrade capability — Swarm-driven tool generation (Phase 5)
Allow Manna to detect a missing tool/API wrapper at runtime and use the Swarm to
generate, validate, and activate the new tool — without risking agent health or
creating git noise.

  WHAT ALREADY EXISTS (no changes needed):
    • ITool interface + createTool factory       → packages/tools/types.ts, tool-builder.ts
    • MCP dynamic tool loader                    → packages/mcp/loader.ts (discovers tools at startup)
    • Agent accepts injected ITool[]             → packages/agent/agent.ts constructor
    • Swarm task decomposer                      → packages/swarm/decomposer.ts
    • fs.write + shell tools                     → agent can already write files & run commands
    • Processor middleware                        → can intercept steps for guardrails

  PHASE 5A — MCP-first self-upgrade (safest, ~1 day)
  Leverage the existing MCP loader. When the agent needs a missing service:
    1. Swarm generates a lightweight MCP server script for the new service
       (small Node/TS file exposing tools via @modelcontextprotocol/sdk).
    2. Writes it to a staging directory (e.g. data/mcp-staging/<service-name>/).
    3. Appends an entry to data/mcp-servers.json.
    4. Triggers MCP reload (new function: reloadMCPTools in packages/mcp/loader.ts).
    5. New tools appear in the agent's tool list — no restart, no code merge.
  Guardrails:
    - Staged servers are disabled by default (add "enabled": false in config).
    - Human toggles "enabled": true after review.
    - Health check (packages/mcp/health.ts) must pass before tools are usable.
  Files to touch:
    - packages/mcp/loader.ts        → add reloadMCPTools() + "enabled" field support
    - packages/tools/ (new file)    → mcp.generate.ts meta-tool (~100 LOC)

  PHASE 5B — Native tool registry + codegen (~2-3 days, after 5A is stable)
  Add a mutable ToolRegistry so the agent can register tools at runtime without restart.
    Step 1: ToolRegistry class (~50 LOC)
      - packages/tools/registry.ts
      - Map<string, ITool> with register / unregister / all / get methods.
      - Agent constructor takes registry instead of frozen ITool[].
      - Small refactor in packages/agent/agent.ts (~20 LOC change).
    Step 2: generate_tool meta-tool (~150 LOC)
      - packages/tools/tool.generate.ts
      - Input: serviceName, serviceDescription, apiSpec (OpenAPI snippet or docs URL).
      - LLM generates tool code using the createTool pattern.
      - Writes to packages/tools/<serviceName>.ts via fs.write.
      - Validates: TypeScript compile check or lightweight sandbox eval.
      - Returns { status: 'pending_review', filePath } by default.
    Step 3: Activation policy (~50 LOC)
      - packages/tools/activation-policy.ts
      - canActivateImmediately(toolCode): boolean
      - Block if: uses fs, net, child_process, eval, or unknown imports.
      - Allow if: pure HTTP fetch to allowlisted domains with read-only verbs.
      - Default: always require review (return false).

  PHASE 5C — Safety & operational guardrails (alongside 5B)
    - Per-tool budget: max calls/min, max spend, max concurrency.
    - Kill switch per tool (registry.disable(name)).
    - Global circuit breaker: if failure rate spikes, degrade gracefully.
    - Observability: track success rate, p95 latency, token/cost per tool.
    - Signed tool manifests: registry only loads signed + approved tools.

  PHASE 5D — Git-friendly PR workflow (optional, for production deployments)
    When generate_tool produces a new tool file:
      1. Create branch: tooling/add-<service-name>.
      2. Commit generated tool + tests + threat-model checklist.
      3. Open PR automatically (requires GitHub token in env).
      4. CI runs lint/test/security scan.
      5. Human approval required (CODEOWNERS).
      6. On merge: tool is disabled by default until manually toggled on.
    Rules:
      - One tool per PR, conventional commit label (tool:add).
      - Auto-changelog entry.
      - Progressive rollout: off → canary (1-5%) → full.
      - Automatic rollback on error/latency/security threshold breach.

  ESTIMATED TOTAL: ~250-300 LOC new code + small Agent refactor.
  RECOMMENDED ORDER: 5A → 5B → 5C → 5D (each phase is independently useful).
